 ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":45,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Robert Waddeley was born before 1410, in Stokesley, Yorkshire, England. He married Lady Robert Waddeley x before 1425, in Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter."},"et":{"before 1410–":"enne 1410–Surnud","1404–Female":"1404–Surnud","1425–Female":"1425–Surnud","1410–Male":"1410–Surnud","1404":"1404","1425":"1425","1455":"1455","before 1410":"enne 1410","1410":"1410","Bef 1425":"enne 1425","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Hornby, Yorkshire, England":"Hornby, Yorkshire, England","Stokesley, Yorkshire, England":"Stokesley, Yorkshire, England"},"fi":{"before 1410–":"ennen vuotta 1410–Kuollut","1404–Female":"1404–Kuollut","1425–Female":"1425–Kuollut","1410–Male":"1410–Kuollut","1404":"1404","1425":"1